In the first glance, it seems like this is like maybe three unrelated stories.

20:17.222 --> 20:26.033
But whenever in scripture you find like a story, a narrative kind of bookended with the same character, it's usually a hint that you should take that all together, which is what we're doing here.

20:26.714 --> 20:29.237
And there's kind of this thread woven through it.

20:29.297 --> 20:34.904
But you see this scene where the famine right there in the middle of this famine, they're not quite through it yet.

20:35.765 --> 20:40.050
And these people come to Joseph and like, hey, we need food.

20:40.130 --> 20:42.633
He said, well, you got to pay for this food, so they pay for it.

20:43.054 --> 20:45.537
And they come back the next year, and they ran out of money.

20:45.697 --> 20:47.399
He says, OK, we can barter, we can trade.

20:47.980 --> 20:51.544
So you take a couple cows, you can get some food.

20:52.105 --> 20:53.887
And they come back again, right?

20:53.907 --> 20:55.789
They're out of money.

20:56.790 --> 20:57.952
They have nothing else to trade.

20:58.092 --> 21:01.496
All they have, this says, is their land in themselves.

21:02.678 --> 21:07.123
And so they sell their land in themselves to Joseph.

21:07.143 --> 21:09.426
And it's kind of an interesting scene.

21:09.890 --> 21:11.752
The more you think about it, the more it's a little uncomfortable.

21:11.933 --> 21:12.794
It's like, that's kind of mean.

21:13.595 --> 21:15.016
Joseph, you couldn't just give them some food.

21:15.036 --> 21:16.498
They're hungry, they're about to die, it says.

21:17.580 --> 21:30.456
It looks like these Joseph is exploiting them, that in their greatest time of need, where they will literally die if they do not eat, this isn't just like they're hungry, they will die if they don't eat.

21:33.119 --> 21:36.083
Joseph's like, don't got anything else where you can sell yourself to me.

21:36.103 --> 21:38.546
It seems like he's exploiting them.

21:40.802 --> 21:42.684
to the point where they're like bias and he does.

21:42.804 --> 21:47.128
And it's an interesting scene.

21:48.589 --> 21:50.511
The reality of death is before them.

21:51.912 --> 21:53.954
And in the reality of death, what do they do?

21:53.994 --> 21:56.757
They make themselves dependent on the state.

21:57.938 --> 22:02.442
We're now even in perpetuity, they're gonna owe one fifth of their produce to Pharaoh.

22:03.663 --> 22:06.006
Again, this sounds harsh, it sounds cruel.

22:06.866 --> 22:09.569
Sounds like he's taken advantage of him, but look at how they respond.

22:09.589 --> 22:10.770
Look at how they view this.

22:11.202 --> 22:18.010
Verse 25, it says, and they said, you have saved our lives.

22:19.152 --> 22:21.975
May it please my Lord, we will be servants to Pharaoh.

22:23.477 --> 22:25.439
Does that sound like people who are bummed out?

22:26.741 --> 22:29.584
Does that sound like people who have been taken advantage of?

22:30.966 --> 22:35.852
No, they didn't look at Joseph like a great exploiter or a presser.

22:35.912 --> 22:37.273
They look at him as a savior.

22:38.835 --> 22:39.957
This is not exploitation.

22:39.977 --> 22:41.138
This is actually mercy.

22:41.602 --> 22:42.263
and kindness.

22:43.204 --> 22:46.128
Especially in this ancient day, this is how debt would work.

22:46.649 --> 22:48.412
This is how slavery would work.

22:48.432 --> 22:51.076
It would be like, hey, you've incurred a great debt.

22:51.897 --> 22:53.018
You owe money.

22:54.120 --> 22:55.342
What do you do with that debt?

22:55.402 --> 22:56.363
How do you pay that debt off?

22:56.403 --> 22:59.087
Well, you would work for this person for free.

22:59.127 --> 23:01.450
You'd become enslaved to them, an indentured servitude.

23:01.490 --> 23:03.954
And then in time,

23:04.610 --> 23:06.693
you'll be able to work off that debt as you work for them.

23:06.733 --> 23:07.515
It's a great kindness.

23:07.575 --> 23:10.960
It's closer to an employer-employee relationship than what we think of.

23:10.980 --> 23:19.233
When we think of slavery, we think of the transatlantic slave trade, which has slave trade, just to be very different than the slavery that's talked about in scripture.

23:19.594 --> 23:20.175
Very different.

23:20.676 --> 23:23.160
For those of you who've been around, you hear me say this before.

23:23.220 --> 23:32.114
I'll probably say it every time we come to this because it's such a hot topic and it probably always will be in the life of our country for as long as this country exists.

23:32.290 --> 23:37.177
But that kind of this transatlantic slave trade was always actually forbidden in Scripture.

23:38.038 --> 23:42.845
I can say that with confidence because the God's law forbids man stealing.

23:43.806 --> 23:51.717
And the whole transatlantic trade, the whole slave system was predicated on men being stolen and then sold and then sold again.

23:51.777 --> 23:56.423
So that system was always against the biblical norm.

23:56.464 --> 23:57.805
This is a very different system.

23:57.845 --> 24:01.170
This system that you find of slavery in Scripture is actually incredibly kind.

24:02.114 --> 24:04.898
incredibly just and incredibly honoring.

24:05.639 --> 24:09.825
To think, imagine if I owed an insane debt, let's say, oh, you $100,000.

24:09.885 --> 24:12.669
How am I going to pay that off?

24:13.550 --> 24:14.952
Well, I'm probably not.

24:14.972 --> 24:16.153
So what do you do in that scenario?

24:16.173 --> 24:20.940
Well, it's like you can honor that person to say, hey, I'm going to let you earn this to work this off.

24:22.182 --> 24:29.332
And then what would happen is in the year of Jubilee in the seventh year, they would actually forgive debts and slaves would become free.

24:29.392 --> 24:30.994
But you know what would happen oftentimes?

24:31.714 --> 24:38.244
A slave would say, hey, my life with this master was way better than when I was trying to do this farm situation on my own.

24:38.985 --> 24:44.974
So I'm going to, at the end of the seven years, you can be free or you can say, no, I'm just going to be with the rest of life and we're going to work together.

24:45.535 --> 24:47.317
This is how this system worked.

24:47.337 --> 25:01.298
And so this system here, which to our modern ears looks cruel, is actually incredibly kind, incredibly humanizing to create this system where you can work off your debt and be provided for by a good master.

25:01.858 --> 25:09.368
In this whole situation of their dependency, the threat of death is what exposed this deep truth of the world.

25:10.389 --> 25:14.114
Because there is a reality that none of us are free.

25:14.915 --> 25:16.858
In the sense, we're all dependent on something.

25:17.298 --> 25:20.122
Scripture actually says we're all enslaved to something.

25:20.142 --> 25:21.784
We're all yoked to something.

25:22.846 --> 25:29.074
You know, when Scripture uses that term yoked, the thing that pops into my head is an egg yoke.

25:29.634 --> 25:30.736
That's not what it's talking about.

25:30.776 --> 25:33.400
If that is with the image that pops in your head, it's okay.

25:33.420 --> 25:34.902
It was for me for many years.

25:34.962 --> 25:37.046
I knew it didn't mean that, but I love eggs.

25:37.747 --> 25:40.872
So if you're not an egg guy, then you won't think about that.

25:40.892 --> 25:48.444
But to be yoked to something is like you have this two oxen, you know, they got that big wooden thing that connects them together.

25:48.905 --> 25:49.746
It's a connection.

25:50.338 --> 25:53.302
And so if you're yoked to something, it's like where one goes, the other one goes.

25:53.542 --> 25:54.844
You share each other's strengths.

25:54.864 --> 25:55.925
You share each other's burden.

25:55.945 --> 25:57.066
You're going in the same direction.

25:57.106 --> 25:59.049
That's what that's talking about.

25:59.469 --> 26:00.991
And there's this truth of scripture here.

26:01.011 --> 26:02.473
You're always yoked to something.

26:02.493 --> 26:03.775
You're always serving something.

26:04.115 --> 26:06.558
No one is truly free to be able to do whatever they want.

26:08.000 --> 26:12.025
Before this debt that they incurred with the state, they were dependent on so many things.

26:12.926 --> 26:15.149
You were not thinking about it, like your daily bread, water.

26:15.629 --> 26:19.474
We can't make the water come from the sky, for our crops.

26:20.610 --> 26:27.898
where there's so many things, you're depending upon the sun to turn, if the sun to rise, you can't control the weather.

26:27.938 --> 26:37.568
The coming death, their coming death made them realize that they actually have no control in their life.

26:38.349 --> 26:41.913
This exposed the reality from it, that they are dependent on something else.

26:44.336 --> 26:46.418
And in this moment, they chose to depend

26:46.658 --> 26:48.961
to yoke themselves to Joseph in his kindness.

26:48.981 --> 26:51.784
They chose to yoke themselves to him, to him to be their master.

26:54.908 --> 27:00.274
So we're all slaves to something, but only one master can give you a slavery that leads to freedom.

27:00.895 --> 27:07.263
You know, Romans 6 says it this way, that we're slaves to sin, we're slaves to righteousness.

27:10.126 --> 27:14.151
And only one kind of slavery will actually look to freedom, and this is what it looks like.

27:14.211 --> 27:16.434
And actually in Romans 6, 18,

27:18.018 --> 27:24.967
Probably should have had this bookmarked ahead of time so you can watch how slow I am turning to Bible verses.

27:24.987 --> 27:26.349
Not winning one of those sword drills.

27:29.293 --> 27:32.457
I know that even the babies are crying because how slow this is.

27:35.201 --> 27:37.584
What I say Roman six, something six to 18.

27:38.345 --> 27:40.128
Roman six 18 says this.

27:42.491 --> 27:47.858
And having been set free from sin, have become slaves of righteousness.

27:48.930 --> 27:53.957
There's this truth here where freedom comes through being enslaved to Christ.

27:54.417 --> 27:56.340
And you might say, well, how is that free?

27:57.361 --> 27:58.583
Because of where it leads you.

27:59.304 --> 28:00.486
It leads you to life.

28:01.267 --> 28:04.711
The question is not do I have a master, am I enslaved?

28:04.731 --> 28:06.894
But the question is always, who is your master?

28:08.036 --> 28:11.500
And your fate will always be the same as your master.

28:13.043 --> 28:18.610
This is where only slavery to Christ, only being enslaved and yoked to Him, can we taste life?

28:19.202 --> 28:23.428
Because what a Christ do, yes, he died, but what came out on the other side of death was his life.

28:23.468 --> 28:28.396
And as we are yoked to him, we do experience death, but that death is the very thing that leads to life.

28:29.758 --> 28:35.306
And Joseph himself here is a preview of what Christ is offering to you and to me.

28:37.049 --> 28:39.673
We come to Jesus, needy, broken.

28:40.314 --> 28:41.015
We have nothing.

28:41.415 --> 28:43.298
All we have is ourselves.

28:43.899 --> 28:46.643
We're this living sacrifice, as Romans talks about.

28:47.364 --> 28:48.466
We come to him, needy,

28:48.578 --> 28:49.359
We have nothing.

28:49.399 --> 28:51.881
We need food lest we die.

28:51.921 --> 28:53.483
And what does Jesus offer you?

28:53.503 --> 28:55.545
He offers Himself as that food.

28:56.706 --> 28:59.249
He tells us that I am the bread of life.

29:01.711 --> 29:03.433
This is what He offers you lest you die.

29:03.493 --> 29:04.954
He gives you life.

29:07.177 --> 29:09.038
The question is, will you follow a good master?

29:09.559 --> 29:11.020
Christ, who dies for you?

29:12.742 --> 29:14.504
Who leads you through death to life?

29:14.604 --> 29:16.626
Or are you going to follow one who exploits you?

29:17.474 --> 29:18.816
Only Christ leads to life.

29:20.478 --> 29:24.042
And Jesus invites us into this in Matthew 11 when he says, take my yoke.

29:25.023 --> 29:27.266
He said, take this, take this upon you.

29:30.270 --> 29:31.231
I will carry it for you.

29:32.913 --> 29:40.523
And when you yoke yourself to him, when you live in him, yes, you will taste death, but as he rose again, so will you rise again.

29:41.564 --> 29:46.130
So true freedom is not found in autonomy because autonomy is not real.

29:47.426 --> 29:49.668
It's an autonomy is an illusion.

29:51.871 --> 29:55.675
Freedom is found when we accept what is true, that we are dependent creatures.

29:57.357 --> 30:03.844
Nothing makes that point quite as clear as the reality of death that you cannot escape.

30:05.986 --> 30:06.787
You cannot escape it.

30:06.807 --> 30:13.695
It's one of those things where we're uncomfortable with it, because it's sad, it's separation, and we should be uncomfortable with it.

30:13.715 --> 30:15.357
I'm not really dealing with this side of death.

30:15.377 --> 30:16.658
Death is an enemy of God.

30:17.986 --> 30:19.327
It's not the way it's supposed to be.

30:19.347 --> 30:22.811
There's actually a great book called It's Not the Way It's Supposed to Be by Cornelius.

30:22.891 --> 30:26.434
Planting girdle, which deals with this topic, death should not exist, but it does exist.

30:26.455 --> 30:27.976
We live in a world that is still fallen.

30:28.917 --> 30:30.979
There's a reality that we cannot escape on our own.

30:31.019 --> 30:34.122
And it teaches you how dependent you are.

30:36.104 --> 30:37.125
You're dependent creatures.

30:39.708 --> 30:45.874
And as you're dependent creature, yoke yourself, depend on the one who can actually lead you through death

30:46.818 --> 30:47.940
to life on the other side.

30:49.042 --> 30:57.114
So what death does, as a way of focusing that, to see our need for dependence, to see our need for master, to choose the right master in Christ who will lead you to life.

30:59.779 --> 31:07.871
Which leads to the third and final thing that death, I think, teaches us in this passage, which is the reality of death clarifies our hope.

31:09.694 --> 31:14.642
The reality of death clarifies our hope.

31:15.618 --> 31:18.503
We see this at this end from verse 27 to 31.

31:20.006 --> 31:21.409
This final scene here begins.

31:21.429 --> 31:25.757
It's kind of this interesting detail that thus Israel settled in the land of Egypt and land of Goshen.

31:26.919 --> 31:30.646
And they gained possession in it and were fruitful and multiplied greatly.

31:31.828 --> 31:36.237
Again, whenever you get these repeated phrases throughout Scripture, it should perk your ears up.

31:37.178 --> 31:39.122
You've heard fruitful multiply.

31:39.426 --> 31:43.591
I mean, first you hear it in the opening couple chapters of Genesis, here again to Noah.

31:44.051 --> 31:47.935
Abraham gets it, the patriarchs of Genesis get this mantra.

31:48.316 --> 31:49.818
And now what do you see though?

31:49.838 --> 31:52.020
This isn't just a command, it's actually a description.

31:52.881 --> 31:54.383
They were fruitful, they did multiply.

31:54.423 --> 31:55.244
This is happening.

31:55.284 --> 31:58.287
Like the promise that God gave to Abraham is actually happening.

31:58.307 --> 31:59.989
They are multiplying greatly.

32:00.009 --> 32:08.178
In fact, they multiply so greatly that Egypt becomes afraid of them and eventually enslaves them because they've grown so, so greatly.

32:09.762 --> 32:10.423
fulfillment.

32:12.246 --> 32:14.148
The only problem is, where are they?

32:14.669 --> 32:15.430
They're in Egypt still.

32:15.450 --> 32:17.573
They're not in the land that God had promised them.

32:17.613 --> 32:20.277
God promised Abraham and his descendants three things, right?

32:20.337 --> 32:21.819
A land, a people and a blessing.

32:22.340 --> 32:23.181
They seem to be blessed.

32:24.103 --> 32:26.506
They have the people, but they don't have the land.

32:27.988 --> 32:37.362
So I don't know, but I imagine at least some conversation around the water cooler, I probably had those, was, hey, maybe we just stay in Egypt.

32:38.338 --> 32:39.019
This is pretty good.

32:39.319 --> 32:47.547
In fact, why I can say with confidence that they might have said that is because they said that when they were wandering the desert, thinking back on their slavery, they're like, hey, it was better when we were slaves, maybe we'd go back.

32:48.027 --> 32:52.912
That leads me to believe at least some people were thinking, man, Canaan, we don't need to go back there.

32:53.793 --> 32:58.817
Maybe that was just a test, and then this is actually God's promise time, which seemed to be doing pretty well.

32:59.978 --> 33:05.083
I imagine that that was at least in the air, in the water, maybe Egypt's it.

33:06.765 --> 33:07.986
And then Jesus,

33:08.450 --> 33:12.136
Jacob's close to his last words, he speaks, he says this.

33:15.382 --> 33:34.834
When the time drew near that Israel must die, he called his son Joseph and said, if now I have found favor in your sight, put your hand under my thigh and promised to deal kindly and truly with me, do not bury me at Egypt, but let me lie with my fathers, carry me out of Egypt and bury me in their bearing place.

33:37.026 --> 33:38.208
saying, listen, I'm dying soon.

33:38.328 --> 33:40.371
Do not put my bones in the ground here.

33:41.933 --> 33:42.274
Take them.

33:42.855 --> 33:43.516
Take them with you.

33:44.597 --> 33:45.058
Swear it.

33:46.080 --> 33:48.003
And I know these kind of scenes are uncomfortable.

33:48.023 --> 33:49.665
He's putting his hand under a thigh.

33:49.745 --> 33:50.646
What's going on there?

33:51.788 --> 33:52.890
That's how they make covenants.

33:54.052 --> 33:57.397
It's the strongest promise that you can make in this day.

33:57.877 --> 34:01.323
Basically saying, listen, if you don't do this, you will die.

34:02.604 --> 34:03.045
Serious.

34:04.427 --> 34:05.148
Joseph does it.

34:05.389 --> 34:06.290
He says, I swear it.

34:07.234 --> 34:17.486
Making this covenant, this strong contract that I will bring you back, swearing on his life, saying, listen, prosperity here is nice, but you can't take it with you.

34:17.526 --> 34:24.314
Death focuses attention in his hopes on the dreams of his beyond his life.

34:25.515 --> 34:29.040
The dreams that he had for his very bones, which is really interesting for us.

34:29.841 --> 34:33.505
I mean, why does he care what happens to his bones?

34:33.545 --> 34:34.546
I mean, who cares?

34:34.978 --> 34:37.261
You don't know what happens to him once you're gone, you're gone, right?

34:39.123 --> 34:41.366
Why does he care where his bones are buried?

34:41.426 --> 34:44.189
Our natural instinct was to say they don't matter anymore.

34:45.471 --> 34:46.612
So why do they matter to him?

34:47.593 --> 34:52.880
Because the way you treat the dead says a lot about your future hope.

34:55.223 --> 34:59.348
I'll get into this more in a second, but this is historically why Christians have never cremated their dead.

35:00.429 --> 35:04.434
Because they believe that their body will be raised again to new life.

35:05.506 --> 35:08.451
And so you bury your dead in the hope of that claim.

35:08.931 --> 35:09.673
This is Jacob.

35:10.394 --> 35:13.419
Jacob couldn't claim the promised land at the end of his life.

35:16.263 --> 35:18.947
He didn't care if it took his death to claim it.

35:18.967 --> 35:19.628
He would claim it.

35:20.029 --> 35:23.675
He would want his bones buried there to inhabit the land and death.

35:23.835 --> 35:24.075
Why?

35:24.135 --> 35:25.698
Because Egypt is not his home.

35:25.758 --> 35:26.259
He knew this.

35:26.659 --> 35:28.763
Egypt was not the thing that was promised to him.

35:30.405 --> 35:33.330
And so burial in this way is a confession of hope.

35:34.530 --> 35:35.812
that death is not my end.

35:36.753 --> 35:43.662
The only reason you would care about where your bones were is if you believed you were gonna embody them again, which he does.

35:44.363 --> 35:46.446
He's saying, listen, God will keep his promises.

35:47.568 --> 35:53.796
He will bring them back to life where we bury our dead as a testimony of confidence.

35:55.198 --> 35:58.943
It's declaring your hope that God will raise these bones.

36:00.485 --> 36:03.890
That yes, death has stolen someone away from me that I love,

36:05.282 --> 36:06.704
but he will not steal them forever.

36:07.505 --> 36:10.250
Death does not end, its sting is removed.

36:10.610 --> 36:12.994
God will raise his bones, we will dwell with them forever.

36:13.034 --> 36:19.184
What we do with our dead speaks to what we believe about this, that in life or in death, God will fulfill his promises.

36:20.305 --> 36:25.994
The reality of death clarified his hope was not in Egypt, it was in God's promises.

36:28.298 --> 36:33.586
And when the reality of death comes before you, it does the same for you.

36:35.426 --> 36:37.509
It clarifies what you put your hope in.

36:38.471 --> 36:43.017
Do you put your hope in princes and the strength of princes and the mites of kingdoms of man?

36:43.058 --> 36:44.880
Do you put your hope and your wealth?

36:44.920 --> 36:47.424
Do you put your hope in your friends and family?

36:47.444 --> 36:48.806
Where is it that you put your hope?

36:48.866 --> 36:59.282
Or do you put your hope that God is growing his kingdom on earth as it is in heaven, that that will happen in our day or in the days to come, most likely the days to come.

37:01.762 --> 37:04.627
And my bones will not stay in the ground, but they will be raised.

37:04.647 --> 37:06.389
They will be inhabited by me again.

37:06.450 --> 37:09.835
This is going to happen.

37:11.678 --> 37:17.467
When we bury our dead, it's a sort of quiet defiance, not because it's practical.

37:18.709 --> 37:24.178
It's not apparently plots of land to bury our dead if they're not cheap.

37:24.770 --> 37:32.119
But every time we place a body in the ground, we make this quiet declaration that this is not the end, this is not the final resting place of these bones, they will come back.

37:34.102 --> 37:41.351
They're like little seeds of the kingdom, little mustard seeds of the kingdom that we are planting in the earth, and there's nothing more mustard seedy than something dead.

37:42.772 --> 37:46.737
We're placing something dead in the ground and saying it will not stay, that it will burst to new life.

37:48.840 --> 37:51.303
They're mustard seeds of the kingdom that united the Christ.

37:51.783 --> 37:53.906
They are like us claiming this earth.

37:54.466 --> 38:00.835
Just like Jacob being buried back in the promised land was a way for him to claim the land, even in death.

38:02.578 --> 38:05.923
Us, as we are placed in the ground here, is a way of us claiming this earth.

38:05.983 --> 38:16.378
Because the promise that God has made to his people is not just Israel and that one little chunk of land, but that was always meant to be a testimony to the whole earth that is a bit promised to God and to God's people.

38:17.219 --> 38:19.282
It's not as fulfilled in Christ through the church.

38:19.906 --> 38:23.790
So every time we place a body into the ground, we're saying, this belongs to the Lord.

38:24.131 --> 38:25.312
This is the promised land.

38:25.673 --> 38:28.356
This land will be claimed by the Lord one day.

38:29.857 --> 38:33.742
It's our claim of the earth that it belongs to our master.

38:35.184 --> 38:38.227
And this truth is clarified and claimed for us.

38:38.307 --> 38:40.369
This hope is clarified in our death.

38:41.511 --> 38:46.296
You know, you know, Paul has these words for us that to live is Christ and to die is gain.

38:46.336 --> 38:47.858
If those words have ever puzzled you,

38:48.930 --> 38:50.592
To live as Christ, to die is gain.

38:51.433 --> 38:52.574
This is what this is about.

38:53.635 --> 38:58.180
That it's in death that our hope of life is actually seen and claimed by us.

39:00.162 --> 39:01.663
This is why we don't have to fear it.

39:01.703 --> 39:06.488
The way that we face death and deal with death clarifies and signifies your hope.

39:08.751 --> 39:09.692
One more example of this.

39:09.972 --> 39:15.698
Think about, there's a rise in practice of things like euthanasia, right, where people

39:15.874 --> 39:20.340
Getting to the end of their life, maybe they're sick or something, and so I hate to ease the pain, ease the burden on society.

39:20.380 --> 39:21.842
We'll just cut your life short.

39:22.623 --> 39:22.963
Goodbye.

39:24.745 --> 39:27.929
It's a growing practice, but what does that communicate to euthanize somebody?

39:28.050 --> 39:29.712
What does that communicate about your hope?

39:31.374 --> 39:34.418
Well, it says that life is only living if I'm useful to you.

39:35.059 --> 39:37.001
Life's only worth living if I'm not in pain.

39:38.323 --> 39:40.946
Life is about me and me alone.

39:42.946 --> 39:47.112
This is why this is an abomination as a practice to the Christian, to the church.

39:49.294 --> 39:51.698
Death clarifies what we have hope in.

39:52.859 --> 40:03.954
If all we have in life is this, you gotta live and let live while you have it and then you go away, if that's all we had, then euthanasia and those kinds of things, practices make sense.

40:04.735 --> 40:12.946
But if God is the one orchestrating, holding all things together, bringing life and death into life and life and death are in his hands and we can trust him with theirs.

40:15.138 --> 40:19.703
You know, this week I was talking to a friend of mine who's in Virginia, he's a pastor.

40:20.924 --> 40:33.137
And there's a couple in his church who they found out during pregnancy that the child had a rare condition and the chances of that child being born and being able to live were next to nothing.

40:34.138 --> 40:37.242
And so they had to decide, do we abort this child or not?

40:37.742 --> 40:40.645
And the doctor said, hey, you should probably just abort this child.

40:41.667 --> 40:44.850
And they said, no, like listen, we believe in life.

40:45.378 --> 40:49.404
Even if we get one second with this child, we are going to carry it to term.

40:50.406 --> 40:58.558
And the last month of this pregnancy, the woman was several hours away on bed rest in a hospital.

40:59.519 --> 41:04.827
And my buddy gets a call and he starts driving the husband to go meet them because the baby's coming.

41:05.328 --> 41:11.878
And they rush into the hospital and he gets to hold his daughter for probably five seconds.

41:13.240 --> 41:14.482
And she breathes her last.

41:16.322 --> 41:20.989
And people on the outside might look at a story like that and like, why would you do that?

41:22.010 --> 41:28.720
Why would you carry that child's term to spend five seconds with this daughter to put her into the ground?

41:30.102 --> 41:30.362
Why?

41:30.402 --> 41:34.448
She was dead before she was born, so to speak, why?

41:35.429 --> 41:41.518
Because what we do with the dead says something about what we value and what we hope in in this world.

41:42.820 --> 41:44.242
Because our God's the God of life.

41:45.762 --> 41:51.168
And that one child, those five seconds, that's a testimony to the gospel.

41:52.670 --> 41:55.573
There's a real life that's filled with the image-bearing of God.

41:57.915 --> 42:00.098
Because that life, no matter how short, was a gift.

42:03.822 --> 42:09.167
See, death and the reality of death and life clarify so much for us.

42:10.149 --> 42:11.190
It says what you value.

42:11.210 --> 42:12.611
Do you value your own comfort?

42:13.752 --> 42:15.154
Do you value what's easy?

42:16.002 --> 42:18.225
Or do you value those things that are eternal?

42:20.970 --> 42:23.714
I promise you, you're gonna wake up tomorrow morning, you're pregnant, forget everything I said.

42:23.754 --> 42:28.001
And that's most okay, but you should remember a couple of things.

42:29.343 --> 42:32.588
These opportunities to reflect on death are few and far between.

42:32.628 --> 42:39.058
Opportunities to reflect on death do not happen by accident in life.

42:40.258 --> 42:41.400
Don't waste these opportunities.

42:41.560 --> 42:50.874
Death is a fantastic teacher for you, not to steal your hope and to say, this is gonna be sad and we're all gonna die and woe as me, but to remember that death is not our end, the friends.

42:51.595 --> 42:59.707
If you believe that, think of the courage you could have and the fearlessness you can have to live in this world that is against you.

43:02.751 --> 43:07.719
This is what's before you this morning as we consider the life of Jacob in the end of the life of Jacob.

43:07.779 --> 43:09.842
May we be a bold people

43:10.050 --> 43:15.196
who did not ignore this teacher, but let it spur us on the hope and courage in this world.

43:16.478 --> 43:16.918
Pray with me.

43:19.502 --> 43:36.242
Merciful God, we both lament the reality of death in our world, and we also are not afraid of it, because you have stolen its sting

43:36.514 --> 43:39.158
It does not win, you win, your life wins.

43:39.258 --> 43:45.146
May we milk ourselves to you, and as we do, may you carry us through the valley of the shadow of death.

43:45.666 --> 43:47.189
May you help us to fear no evil.

43:48.150 --> 43:56.661
May you give us peace and grace to walk with you in this life, to death, to life beyond.

43:56.702 --> 44:03.250
As we live this way, courageously and fearlessly, may our lives be a testimony to our neighbors.

44:04.252 --> 44:05.173
I pray this in your holy name.

44:05.453 --> 44:05.874
Amen.

